There is a CAS issue: if you don't have an existing CAS login to the site, after you fill in your information in CAS, you get a browser error message `The website encountered an unexpected error. Please try again later. `.

In the watchdog table, we get the following:
```
Call to undefined function curl_init()
CAS_Request_CurlRequest->initAndConfigure()
/var/www/friends_of_pul/releases/20221101185541/sites/all/libraries/CAS/CAS/Request/CurlRequest.php
```

I think this is because apache is still using our PHP 7.4 installation, which doesn't have curl enabled.  Our PHP 8.1 installation does have curl enabled, but apache doesn't have the new PHP module enabled.

Moving this PR back to draft accordingly.

Missing "Required Metadata" doesn't prevent file upload... but validation fails later
"Assertion failed: Input argument is not an HTMLInputElement onloadwff.js"

comments.body:
If it's not hard, factoring this into ERB might be good, though I don't think it's essential.

Related issue:
- #585

@Twade968 there are several issues here. Let me preface everything by saying we (PRDS) did not curate this one, and I'm not sure which submission form was used for it.

I'm looking at the full item record to understand it better: https://dataspace.princeton.edu/handle/88435/dsp015999n626m?mode=full

The dc.contributor.author field was not used. Instead, there are three dc.creator fields in the original record that should be translated to the DataCite Creator field. One of the names listed as a creator was repeated as a contributor, and we do not want to replicate that error. In addition, we typically do not input funding agencies as contributors, so the Creator field you have for the National Science Foundation should be omitted.

The original record has a title as well as an alternative title, and the title field already includes a subtitle, so I do not think that the two title fields should be merged in DataCite. Instead, the alternative title from the original record can be translated as a second title with the type "AlternativeTitle" (see https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-mandatory-properties#3-title). 

For some reason, this record does not have an issue date (which is generally required). However, I can see that the dc.date.accessioned is in 2019, so the DataCite record should have the Publication Year field set to 2019 instead of 2020.

While the original record does have the publisher set to "Princeton University Lewis-Sigler Institute", our current practice is to correct such entries to "Princeton University".

The original record has two description fields filled: abstract and table of contents. My understanding is that for the purposes of migration, we are copying over abstracts as Description Type "Other" and omitting other description fields for now.
👍🏻 to adding this to the README since it's important for local manual testing, and Figgy also has the in its README.

pdc_discovery.title: One Solr node seems to be down

comments.body:
I created a new replica in `lib-solr-prod4` but unfortunately the new replica also reports "recovery failed"

![Screen Shot 2022-11-01 at 10 45 11 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568286/199261668-1683df71-5966-4a43-b565-93d06a8d54d0.png)

The Solr suggestion option seems to detect that we have a problem with this collection and suggest and action to fix it

![Screen Shot 2022-11-01 at 11 08 42 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568286/199267090-58f5bd5c-f01e-473d-a38b-4aa7be738c33.png)

but clicking that button does not fix it. It does add a new replica to the collection but still with the "recovery failed" status and after clicking this button a few times it looks like Solr added a bunch of failed replicas to our collection:

![Screen Shot 2022-11-01 at 11 10 57 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/568286/199267378-526bfb48-d47f-40b2-aff0-633d41b841b2.png)

We could not get a new replica to work on the existing `pdc-discovery-production` collection. We tried deleting the existing replicas and re-creating them in `lib-solr-prod4/5/6` to no avail.

Instead we created a new Solr collection called `pdc-discovery-production-2` with two replicas and that worked perfectly. We then re-indexed the data by running the reindex rake task with SOLR-URL env pointing to `http://lib-solr8-prod.princeton.edu:8983/solr/pdc-discovery-production-2`. 

Once we confirmed the data was reindexed in `pdc-discovery-production-2` we **deleted** the old `pdc-discovery-production` collection and created an alias so that the new `pdc-discovery-production-2` collection is also known as `pdc-discovery-production`, this way the PDC discovery code and configuration does not need to be updated.
